'''Ooe Clan''' (大江氏) is a clan whose name is derived from “Ooe.” Its surname ({{ill|Kabane|de|Kabane|ja|カバネ|qq=draft}}) is of courtier origin.

It has been a noble family from ancient to early modern Japan. “Ooe” is a surname ({{ill|Honsei|de|Honsei|ja|本姓|qq=draft}}) and not a family name ({{ill|Myōji|de|Myōji|ja|苗字|qq=draft}}), similar to clans such as {{ill|Minamoto|de|Minamoto|ja|源氏|lt=Minamoto|lt_ja=源|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Taira|de|Taira|ja|平氏|lt=Taira|lt_ja=平|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Fujiwara Clan|de|Fujiwara‐Clan|ja|藤原氏|lt=Fujiwara|lt_ja=藤原|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Tachibana Clan|de|Tachibana‐Clan|ja|橘氏|lt=Tachibana|lt_ja=橘|qq=draft}}.

== Nara Period ==
{{ill|Ancient|de|Antik|ja|古代|qq=draft}} {{ill|Clan|de|Clan|ja|氏族|qq=draft}} of the {{ill|Tsuchi‐haji Clan|de|Tsuchi‐haji‐Clan|ja|土師氏|qq=draft}} is considered the origin. In the 9th year of {{ill|Enryaku|de|Enryaku|ja|延暦|qq=draft}} (791, the 10th year of the reign of {{ill|Emperor Kanmu|de|Kanmü|ja|桓武天皇|qq=draft}} – {{ill|791|de|791|ja|791年|qq=draft}}), relatives of {{ill|Ooe Shorogami|de|Ooe Shorogami|ja|大枝諸上|lt=Tsuchi‐haji Shorogami|lt_ja=土師諸上|lt_de=Tsuchi‐haji Shorogami|qq=draft}} were granted the surname '''Ooe'''.

== Heian Period ==
In October of {{ill|866|de|866|ja|866年|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Seigan (Japan)|de|Seigan|ja|貞観 (日本)|lt=Seigan|lt_ja=貞観|qq=draft}} 8), {{ill|Ooe Otohito|de|Ooe Otohito|ja|大江音人|lt=Ooe Otohito|lt_ja=大枝音人|qq=draft}} changed his surname from '''Ooe Shorogami''' to '''Ooe''' via a {{ill|Name Change|de|Namensänderung|ja|改姓|qq=draft}}. The rationale was that if a branch ({{ill|Branch|de|Zweig|ja|枝|qq=draft}}) became too large, it might cause the trunk ({{ill|Trunk|de|Stamm|ja|幹|qq=draft}}) of the main family to break (a case of overthrow), which was seen as inauspicious. However, since the Ooe surname had been bestowed by Emperor Kanmu, a complete change was not possible; only the kanji notation was altered while retaining the pronunciation. In addition, the name “Ooe” is said to signify that the family will prosper endlessly like a great river (江).<ref>''{{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|de|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|qq=draft}}'' Seigan 8, October 15</ref>

The Ooe Clan produced many distinguished poets and scholars, and they were held in high esteem by the {{ill|Imperial Court|de|Kaiserhof|ja|朝廷|lt=Imperial Court|lt_ja=朝廷|lt_de=Kaiserhof|qq=draft}}. Among the “Middle Thirty‐Six Poetic Immortals” ({{ill|Middle Thirty‐Six Poetic Immortals|de|Mittlere Sechsunddreißig Dichter|ja|中古三十六歌仙|qq=draft}}) – a selection of the era’s foremost poets – were chosen from the Ooe Clan: {{ill|Ooe Senri (Poet)|de|Ooe Senri (Dichter)|ja|大江千里 (歌人)|lt=Ooe Senri|lt_ja=大江千里|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ooe Masakane|de|Ooe Masakane|ja|大江匡衡|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ooe Kagen|de|Ooe Kagen|ja|大江嘉言|qq=draft}}, and among women, {{ill|Izumi Shikibu|de|Izumi Shikibu|ja|和泉式部|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Akazome Emon|de|Akazome Emon|ja|赤染衛門|qq=draft}} (wife of Masakane). In addition, a great scholar of the Heian period—descended from Ooe Masafusa—is said to have taught {{ill|Military Tactics|de|Militärtaktik|ja|兵法|qq=draft}} to Minamoto no Yoshie (Yahata Tarō) of the {{ill|Kawachi Minamoto Clan|de|Kawachi‐Minamoto|ja|河内源氏|qq=draft}}.

== Later Heian Period ==
In the {{ill|11th Century|de|11. Jahrhundert|ja|11世紀|qq=draft}}, a fixed hierarchy was established with the Fujiwara clan at its apex (via the regency system {{ill|Sesshō and Kampaku|de|Sesshō und Kampaku|ja|摂家|lt=Kampaku|lt_ja=摂関家|lt_de=Kampaku|qq=draft}}), and the Ooe Clan was Ranked at the Fifth Court Rank, serving as regional governors ({{ill|Kunshi|de|Kunshi|ja|国司|qq=draft}}) in local areas—thus placing them among the middle to lower nobility. Moreover, as they also functioned as scholars in the family school ({{ill|Family School|de|Familienschule|ja|家学|qq=draft}}), they produced a number of literary aristocrats ({{ill|Literary Aristocracy|de|Literarischer Adel|ja|文人貴族|qq=draft}}).<ref>Overview of Japanese Intellectual History (Hiroshi Ichikawa)</ref>

== Kamakura Period ==
In {{ill|1184|de|1184|ja|1184年|qq=draft}} (the first year of {{ill|Genryaku|de|Genryaku|ja|元暦|qq=draft}}) the head of the {{ill|Kawachi Minamoto Clan|de|Kawachi‐Minamoto|ja|河内源氏|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|de|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|qq=draft}}, employed {{ill|Ooe Hiromoto|de|Ooe Hiromoto|ja|大江広元|qq=draft}}, a great‐grandson of Ooe Masafusa, and supported his rise through administrative reforms. When Yoritomo established the {{ill|Kamakura Shogunate|de|Kamakura‐Shogunat|ja|鎌倉幕府|qq=draft}}, Hiromoto ascended to the shogunate’s inner circle and acquired vast estates. By distributing these lands among his children, he became the progenitor of the warrior branch of the Ooe Clan, which includes, among others, the {{ill|Mōri Clan|de|Mōri‐Clan|ja|毛利氏|qq=draft}}.

== Later Period ==
[[File:Ichimonjimitsuboshi.png|thumb|right|100px|Ichimonji Triple Star (Nagato Star)]]

The descendants of {{ill|Ooe Hiromoto|de|Ooe Hiromoto|ja|大江広元|lt=Hiromoto|lt_ja=広元|qq=draft}} flourished as warriors in various regions. Among his descendants are the following. In addition, the descendant of Mōri Katsumitsu, the fourth son, from the {{ill|Mōri Clan|de|Mōri‐Clan|ja|毛利氏|qq=draft}}, settled in Yoshida Manor of {{ill|Aki Province|de|Aki‐Provinz|ja|安芸国|qq=draft}}, and from that bloodline emerged the Sengoku daimyo {{ill|Mōri Motonari|de|Mōri Motonari|ja|毛利元就|qq=draft}} and the Toyotomi Shogunate’s Five Elders, including {{ill|Mōri Terumoto|de|Mōri Terumoto|ja|毛利輝元|qq=draft}}. Many families adopted the family crest “Three Stars in One Character,” and numerous branches used the characters {{'''{{ill|Hiro|de|Hiro|ja|広|lt=Hiro|lt_ja=広|lt_de=Hiro|qq=draft}}'''}} and {{'''{{ill|Moto|de|Moto|ja|元|lt=Moto|lt_ja=元|lt_de=Moto|qq=draft}}'''}} as their “reading characters” ({{ill|Tōoriji|de|Tōoriji|ja|通字|lt=Tōoriji|lt_ja=通字|lt_de=Tōoriji|qq=draft}}).

